# Get Read Activity

Resident users may view data from third party integrations in the app. The **Get Read Activity** and **Update Read Activity** endpoints allow residents to acknowledge receipt of external resources and track the resource ids of items they have marked as read.

## `GET /api/v2/units/:unit_id/read-activity`

Returns a paginated list of "read activity" for the currently authenticated resident. Each record includes the type of resource, the id of the resource, and the timestamp which the resident most recently marked the resource as read. If a resource is not present in the returned records, it is an indication that the resident has not acknowledged receipt of the item yet.

### Query String Parameters

All parameters are optional. However, `resource_ids` may not be used unless `resource_type` is also specified.

- `since`: Filter read activity to where the `last_read_at` timestamp is no older than the specified timestamp in ISO 8601 format
- `resource_type`: Filter read activity to the given type of resource
- `resource_ids`: **Requires `resource_type` to be specified.** Filter to only include read activity for the given comma-separated ids
- `page`: Page number
- `limit`: Max records to return per page (default: 100)

### Responses

#### 200 Response

Read activity data is returned as a paginated response, sorted by the `last_read_at` timestamp descending (i.e. with most recent read activity first).

If a resource has never been marked as read by the resident, it will not appear in the result set, even if it is listed in the `resource_ids` query parameter.

Only one record will exist per combination of `resource_type` and `resource_id`, even if it has been marked as read multiple times. The `last_read_at` timestamp will reflect the time the resource was most recently marked as read.

```typescript
{
  records: {
    id: number; // positive integer
    resource_type: string;
    resource_id: string;
    last_read_at: string; // ISO timestamp
  }
  [];
  current_page: number; // positive integer
  total_pages: number; // positive integer
  total_records: number; // non-negative integer
}
```

Example:

```json
{
  "records": [
    {
      "id": 123,
      "resource_type": "service_request",
      "resource_id": "2f73fd90-caf8-4bb0-9758-8912558d9f34",
      "last_read_at": "2023-03-30T23:18:51.983Z"
    }
  ],
  "current_page": 1,
  "total_pages": 1,
  "total_records": 1
}
```

#### 422 Response

A 422 response is returned if invalid data is submitted in the query string parameters.

The response body contains an `errors` array specifying details about the problem. Each error object has the name of the request `field` associated with the error message, a `code` identifying the error, and a human-readable `description`.

Example:

```json
{
  "errors": [
    {
      "code": "required",
      "description": "This field is required when `resource_ids` parameter is specified.",
      "field": "resource_type"
    }
  ]
}
```

#### 403 Response

If the currently authenticated resident does not have access to the unit with the given id, or if the currently authenticated user is not a resident, a 403 status code is returned.

```json
{
  "errors": [
    {
      "code": "forbidden",
      "description": "This action is forbidden."
    }
  ]
}
```

#### 404 Response

If the unit id parameter is not an integer, a 404 status code is returned.

```json
{
  "errors": [
    {
      "code": "not_found",
      "description": "The resource was not found."
    }
  ]
}
```

#### 401 Response

Please use a valid access token in your request before continuing. This may require logging in or using your refresh token to obtain a new access token.

```json
{
  "errors": [
    {
      "code": "unauthorized",
      "description": "Must include valid Authorization credentials"
    }
  ]
}
```

# Get Resident Preferences

Resident users may store custom configuration to tailor their personal app experience. These resident preferences are currently used to persist the resident's preferred arrangement of device and access control and frequently used scenes on their personal dashboard. In the future, other resident preferences may be persisted to this endpoint.

Resident preferences are always scoped to a unit.

## `GET /api/v2/units/:unit_id/resident-preferences`

Will return the currently stored preferences for the currently authenticated resident, for the unit with the given id.

### Responses

#### 200 Response

If a resident has already stored preferences before using the `Set Resident Preferences` endpoint, then their preferences will be returned in the API response body. If the resident has not yet stored preferences against this particular unit, an empty preferences object is returned.

```typescript
{
  updated_at: string; // ISO timestamp
  preferences: Record<string, never> | {
    version: number;
    last_updated: string;
    dashboard: {
      scenes: {
        category: "smart_home_devices";
        type: "scene";
        data: {
          id: number; // positive integer
        };
      }[];
      widgets: (
        | {
          category: "smart_home_devices";
          type: "device";
          data: {
            id: number; // positive integer
          };
        }
        | {
          category: "smart_home_devices";
          type: "home_security";
        }
        | {
          category: "smart_home_devices";
          type: "scenes_list";
        }
        | {
          category: "community";
          type: "broadcast_messages";
        }
        | {
          category: "community";
          type: "service_requests";
        }
        | {
          category: "access";
          type: "my_access";
        }
      )[];
    }
  };
}
```

Examples:

The resident has not yet saved their preferences:

```json
{
  "updated_at": null,
  "preferences": {}
}
```

The resident configured their preferred dashboard widget preferences:

```json
{
  "updated_at": "2023-04-10T23:38:12.075Z",
  "preferences": {
    "version": 1,
    "last_updated": "2023-04-10T23:38:12.075Z",
    "dashboard": {
      "scenes": [
        {
          "category": "smart_home_devices",
          "type": "scene",
          "data": { "id": 100 }
        }
      ],
      "widgets": [
        {
          "category": "smart_home_devices",
          "type": "device",
          "data": { "id": 200 }
        },
        {
          "category": "access",
          "type": "my_access"
        },
        {
